Question: Does the proportion of books in the GoodReads db that lack text reviews differ significantly from 7%?

Step 1 formulate Hypothesis

books_tidy %>% 
  group_by(text_reviews_count) %>% 
  summarise(prop = n() / nrow(books_tidy)) %>% 
  filter(text_reviews_count == 0)

Null Hypothesis

The proportion of books that lack text reviews count is not different to 7% \[ H_0: _{no\ reviews} = 7\% \]

Alternative Hypothesis

The proportion of books that lack text reviews count is different to 7% \[ H_1: _{no\ reviews} \neq 7\% \]

Step 2 Calculate statistics

\[ \frac{number\ of\ books\ with\ no\ text\ review}{total\ number\ of\ books} \]

null_distribution <- books_tidy_prop %>% 
  specify(response = has_no_reviews, success = "TRUE") %>% 
  hypothesise(null = "point", p = 0.07) %>% 
  generate(reps = 5000, type = "draw") %>% 
  calculate(stat = "prop")

null_distribution
Response: has_no_reviews (factor)
Null Hypothesis: point
null_distribution %>% 
  visualise(bins = 30)

observed_stat <- books_tidy_prop %>% 
  specify(response = has_no_reviews, success = "TRUE") %>% 
  calculate(stat = "prop")

observed_stat
Response: has_no_reviews (factor)
null_distribution %>% 
  visualise(bins = 30) +
  shade_p_value(obs_stat = observed_stat, direction = "both") 

p_value <- null_distribution %>% 
  get_p_value(obs_stat = observed_stat$stat, direction = "both")

p_value

Since our p_value (0.026) < alpha (0.05) we can reject the Null hypothesis. Therefore, our proprtion of books without a text review is significantly different.
